---
layout: article
title: Authentication
description: "Identity and session management for Appwrite projects: credential-based and passwordless flows, MFA, SSR-aware clients, and OAuth 2 across 30+ providers (GitHub, Google, Microsoft, Apple, and others). Built-in teams support multi-tenancy, invite flows, and org-scoped permissions; labels align with Databases and Storage authorization rules."
back: /docs
---

Appwrite Authentication (AKA Appwrite Auth) is the control plane for principals in your project: account lifecycle, session establishment, and the primitives downstream Appwrite services use when authorizing reads and writes.

Primary sign-in is available through one API: email and password, SMS and email OTP, magic links, guest [anonymous](/docs/products/auth/anonymous) sessions, and patterns suited to server-rendered clients.

[Multifactor authentication (MFA)](/docs/products/auth/mfa) adds server-verified second factors on eligible primary flows. MFA policy and enforcement use the same Console and API model as other Authentication settings.

OAuth 2 integrates 30+ providers, including major consumer and enterprise IdPs (GitHub, Google, Microsoft, Apple) and common developer or collaboration identities (for example Slack, Discord). Provider setup is done in the Console; the redirect-based client flow is documented under [OAuth 2 login](/docs/products/auth/oauth2).

Teams map membership to `team` scopes in [Databases](/docs/products/databases) and [Storage](/docs/products/storage) for multi-tenant products, shared workspaces, and org boundaries. [Team invites](/docs/products/auth/team-invites) support email-based onboarding, roles, and acceptance flows. Partitioning and permission patterns are covered in [Teams](/docs/products/auth/teams) and [Multi-tenancy](/docs/products/auth/multi-tenancy).

[Labels](/docs/products/auth/labels) expose coarse attributes (tiers, entitlements, feature flags) for use in rules. [Preferences](/docs/products/auth/preferences) store built-in account key-value fields (locale, theme, notification toggles) so common settings do not require a separate profile table. Verification, impersonation, and related server APIs are described in the linked workflow guides.

